Q: Blazor Checkbox two-way binding and change event A: <p>Here's a slightly more verbose version of <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/users/13688419/coderr">CoderR's</a> answer <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/77404350">here</a>.
The benefit here is that you don't need to assign/bind a variable to the checkbox state and instead can just pass the value as a function parameter. It makes use of the <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/operators/null-coalescing-operator" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Null-Coalescing Operator</a> to assign a fallback when casting the 'Value' <code>object</code> to a <code>bool</code> (which could result in <code>null</code>)</p>
<pre><code>&lt;input
    class=&quot;form-check-input&quot; 
    type=&quot;checkbox&quot; 
    @onchange=&quot;@((args) =&gt; CheckboxChanged((bool?)args.Value ?? true))&quot;
/&gt;

@code{
      private void CheckboxChanged(bool checked)
      {
           Console.WriteLine($&quot;Checkbox changed {checked}&quot;);
      }
}
</code></pre>
